The Superb White Burgundies of the 1964 and 1962 Vintages

The 1962 white Burgundies are truly wonderful — light, racy and with more bouquet than even the excellent ’61s; they are not as long-lived as the ’61s, but are perhaps better balanced, quicker to mature. They will bring delight to the wine drinker for the next three or four years.

The report is now in on the 64s white Burgundies. They are generally soft, not high in acidity and therefore designed to be consumed young. One must pick carefully here because there are a few fail- ures, as well as outstanding successes. The Chablis and Pouilly Fuisse of Drouhin are both superb. Alexis Lichine reports that the ’64 Pouilly Fuisse of Mathias is one of the outstanding successes of the 1964 vintage.
